{"questionId":"27678","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider a three-digit code <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>c</mi></math>, where each of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> is assigned one of&nbsp;the values <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>, where each of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> is assigned one of&nbsp;the values <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>. Assume that no value is repeated.</p>\n<p>Consider the case where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> has a factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence or otherwise, sketch the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>, clearly showing the&nbsp;coordinates of any intercepts with the axes.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p style=\"padding-left:120px;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/830738f7666ed07ad0b5ae4393b8c57ed5328fa6.png\"></p>\n<p><br>positive cubic shape with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>-intercept at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercept at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and local maximum point anywhere between&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>local minimum point at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Accept answers from an approach based on calculus.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27678","referenceCode":"22N.1.AHL.TZ0.11b.iv","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence or otherwise, sketch the graph of y=P(x), clearly showing the coordinates of any intercepts with the axes.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.iv","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.12—Factor and remainder theorems, sum and product of roots"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}